			<div id="post-3523" class="hentry p3 post publish author-c4chaos category-open-practice category-spirituality y2009 m10 d22 h04">
				<h3 class="entry-title"><a href="http://www.c4chaos.com/2009/10/the-science-of-enlightenment-the-pathless-land/" title="Permalink to The Science of Enlightenment: The Pathless Land" rel="bookmark">The Science of Enlightenment: The Pathless Land</a></h3>
				<div class="entry-date"><abbr class="published" title="2009-10-22T23:03:52+0000">Thursday, October 22nd, 2009</abbr></div>
				<div class="entry-content">
<p>Anyone who has taken a serious study and practice of meditation inevitably encounters a lot of paradoxes along the way, especially when it comes to the concept of enlightenment. Different schools of spirituality put different emphasis on how to view enlightenment. Some schools (e.g. nondual traditions, like Mahayana, Advaita Vedanta, Dzogchen) view enlightenment as an [&hellip;]</p>
